Add -dump-symbols and -dump-fec flags to pocket_trk for LSIS-AFS interop test vectors

Bundled with the LSIS-AFS Test Vectors v0.4.0 release.  Adds two opt-in
CLI flags to pocket_trk and one small bypass that lets the FEC dump
cover all FIDs:

  -dump-symbols <path>  Emit the raw 6000-symbol AFS-D payload (sync
                        prefix + SB1 + interleaved SB2/SB3/SB4) to a
                        file as one uint8 per symbol (value 0 or 1, no
                        header, append-on-each-frame).  Hooks at the
                        entry of decode_AFSD_frame() — the latest point
                        at which the received symbol stream is still in
                        on-air (pre-deinterleave) order.  Polarity is
                        normalised via XOR with the receiver's chosen
                        lock polarity (`rev`) so the output always
                        matches the canonical transmit-side stream.
                        These bytes are byte-equivalent to
                        frames/frame_*.bin[64:6064] in the LSIS-AFS
                        test-vectors repo (channel-bit oracle).

  -dump-fec <path>      Emit the post-LDPC, post-CRC SB2 + SB3 + SB4
                        data bits (1176 + 846 + 846 = 2868 bytes per
                        successful frame, no CRC trailers, no header).
                        Hooks immediately after each subframe's
                        sdr_decode_LDPC_AFS_SF{2,3} + test_CRC succeeds.
                        These bytes are byte-equivalent to
                        inputs/frame_*_input.bin in the LSIS-AFS
                        test-vectors repo (post-FEC bit oracle).

Companion change in decode_AFSD_frame: upstream's sync_AFS_SF1_FID0
only matches FID=0 SB1 codewords; for FID>0 frames (e.g. the LSIS-AFS
test-vectors at FID=3), the function bails before LDPC with "TOI NOT
FOUND".  The LDPC and CRC stages are FID-agnostic block codes, so
SB2/SB3/SB4 still decode correctly given the (FID-independent) sync
polarity already determined upstream by sync_frame().  When -dump-fec
is set, we therefore proceed past the SB1 search with a dummy toi=0
so the FEC dump covers all FIDs.  Receiver PVT/TOW state ends up wrong
for those frames (toi is used downstream in update_tow()), which the
LSIS-AFS test-vectors verifier does not consume.  When -dump-fec is
NOT set, upstream behaviour is restored exactly.

Together these three changes exercise the full receive chain
end-to-end: acquisition + tracking + sync detection + symbol
demodulation (-dump-symbols) + deinterleave + LDPC + CRC validation
(-dump-fec, all FIDs).  Every layer's output is bit-exactly comparable
to the corresponding shipped test vector.

Pinned upstream SHA: 5b23809f30d68518b7fad7a564fd0fac57cc497d.

The patch is intentionally narrow (two CLI flags + four fwrite hooks +
two global FILE*s + one FID-bypass) so it survives minor upstream
churn.  The patch is NOT submitted upstream; it lives only in the
LSIS-AFS Test Vectors harness and is applied at build time by
verify_pocketsdr_decode.py.

License: BSD-2-Clause (matches the upstream PocketSDR-AFS license).

---
